"Notation: <br> <font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> 'What we enter into sage' (note, we do not enter the 'sage:' part) <br> >>> 'The result that is returned by sage' <br> <br> To create a vector in sage, say vector v, we type <br> <font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> v = matrix([[1],[3],[1]]) <br> To put it another way <br> <font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> v = matrix([[$x_1$], [$x_2$], . . . ,[$x_n$]]) <br> Notice that each component is enclosed by a set of square braces, the list of components is enclosed by a set of square braces and everything is enclosed by parentheses. <br> To see the vector we just entered in human form, type <br> <font color = 'green'>sage:</font color> show(v)"